The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), citing Ukrainian officials, said on Tuesday that it was becoming “increasingly urgent” to rotate some of the 210 technical personnel and guards at the Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant who have been working there since Russian forces took control of the site two weeks ago.

Ukrainian authorities informed the IAEA that the staff at Chernobyl had access to food, water, and medicine “to a limited extent,” but their condition was worsening.

The agency’s director general “indicated” that the IAEA has stopped receiving data transmissions from monitoring systems installed at the Chernobyl plant. The agency added that it was “looking into the status” of similar monitoring systems installed in other sites in Ukraine.

